Russian President Vladimir Putin signed a law on the introduction of administrative liability for violation of the terms and order of payment for goods (works, services) in the procurement for state and municipal needs.
This law is intended to solve a very acute problem of non-fulfillment of its obligations by customers in the implementation of state and municipal procurement.
Two years ago, the situation when entrepreneurs could not get paid for already executed state and municipal contracts was widespread.
At the same time, the Russian President instructed the Prosecutor General's office to take the problem under special control.
Because the businessmen themselves could not cope with unscrupulous customers who concluded contracts not supported by financing, tried in every way to evade their payment obligations and included illegal conditions in the contracts.
The problem was systemic in the whole country.
In 2015 in the interest of protecting the rights of businesses to obtain payment for public order the Prosecutor's office made 9.7 thousand views, the results of their review to the disciplinary charges brought against 4,5 thousand officers, administrative - 533, to the investigating authorities for the organization of procedural checks presented 75 reports, 46 of them prosecuted.
As a result, the debt to entrepreneurs was repaid in the amount of more than 66 billion rubles.
And these huge sums were not accumulated as a result of non-payment of multi-billion contracts.
Numerous, systematic delays in payment of services to entrepreneurs for much more modest sums led to fabulous debts.
Here is a typical case.
The head of a small company won a competition for the provision of social transportation services for several million rubles.
The person invested all his working capital, fully fulfilled the obligations, but did not receive the money on time.
The result is a growing financial com of debts on wages, taxes, loans, which would have led to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur had not asked for help to the Prosecutor's office.
Now in a number of regions the problem was managed to be leveled as much as possible.
Nevertheless, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of debt under state and municipal contracts, identified by prosecutors of the Russian Federation, amounted to about 27.4 billion rubles.
In regions where debt indicators continue to reach critical values, the Prosecutor's office works in the mode of manual anti-crisis management.
The Prosecutor General personally conducts field meetings with representatives of local authorities, where all violations revealed by prosecutors and measures for their immediate elimination are subject to examination.
Such operational meetings have already been held this year in Yaroslavl and Yekaterinburg.
The implementation of the Federal law No. 189-FZ "on amendments to the code of administrative offences of the Russian Federation regarding the establishment of administrative liability of the customer's officials for violation of the terms and order of payment for goods (works, services) in the implementation of procurement for state and municipal needs", which was signed by the President of Russia last week, will be able to improve the payment discipline of public customers.
The draft law was developed by the Ministry of economic development on the initiative of the Prosecutor General.
The new law will Supplement the code of the Russian Federation on administrative offences with an article that provides for a fine of 30 thousand to 50 thousand rubles for violation by the official of the customer of the term and the order of payment for goods, works and services in state and municipal procurement.
And if the official has already been subjected to administrative punishment for a similar offense, he will be disqualified for a period of one to two years.
All prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation have already been instructed to ensure the application of these legislative innovations in practice.
The civil rights group has announced a warning on the movement in Missouri
The national Association for the advancement of colored people has issued a warning to colored people traveling to Missouri because of discriminatory state policies and racist attacks.
The group's statement reads as follows:"a warning For travelers of The national Association for the advancement of colored people, valid until August 28, 2017, calls on African-American travelers, guests, and citizens of Missouri to be particularly careful and exercise increased caution when traveling around the state in connection with a number of questionable racist incidents that have recently occurred throughout the state and are cited here."
According to the National Association for the advancement of colored people, to declare a warning on the movement of the group led to the recently adopted Missouri law, because of which people became more difficult to win claims for discrimination, and what law enforcement agencies of the state disproportionately often choose their objects of minorities.
"You have people who are subject to human rights violations.
They are stopped on the roads because of the color of the skin, they are beaten and killed," Rod chapel, President of the national Association for the advancement of the colored population of Missouri, told the Kansas city star newspaper.
"We hear complaints more often than ever."
This is the first warning of this kind announced by the organization in relation to the us state.
The panel referred to incidents such as the racial humiliation of black students At the University of Missouri and the death of 20-year-old Tory Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died under suspicious circumstances earlier this year after running out of gas while traveling around the state, and Missouri state police arrested him without charge of the crime.
The warning also mentions a recent report by the Missouri attorney General's office that black drivers are 75 percent more likely to be stopped on the road than white drivers.
"The purpose of the warning is for people to be aware of the situation and to warn their relatives and friends and colleagues about what might happen in Missouri," chapel said.
"People need to be prepared in one way or another, whether they take money with them for bail or tell relatives that they are traveling across the state."
According to the latest data from the FBI's hate crime reporting program, 100 hate crimes were reported in Missouri in 2015, making the state the sixteenth in the state for the number of such violations.
Also, the travel warning is a response to the new Missouri law, after which it will be more difficult to bring a case against a legal person for housing or employment discrimination.
Earlier, The American civil liberties Union (ACLU) announced warnings to travelers across Texas and Arizona after those States passed new immigration control laws that required local law enforcement to arrest people for violating immigration laws, which, according to the ACLU, was supposed to increase the number of checks on racial grounds.
Movement warnings are usually issued by the Department of State for other countries, but recently public organizations have resorted to this measure in response to certain laws and trends within the United States.
