Blocking critics on Facebook: don't run for public office if you're not ready to listen to criticism from voters
The founder of our country understood what the critical press is.
Americans loved George Washington, but it did not prevent them to criticize him for everything from domestic policy to its political principles.
Criticism his, of course, irritated.
But he didn't shut his mouth to his critics.
Because back in 1783, Washington said, "you can take away the freedom of speech and we, deaf and dumb, will be led like sheep to slaughter."
Now I will go to the Governor of Maryland Larry Hogan, who should try to be more like Washington.
Hogan's subordinates blocked and erased posts from at least 450 people who expressed their opinions on his official Facebook page.
And this week, the American civil liberties Union sued him for it.
Subordinates of the Governor called this claim insignificant, and the comment on the Internet was written in the spirit of "well and that".
"It's just Facebook," many will say.
But it's important.
And that's especially important when it comes to a guy like Hogan.
He's a surprisingly popular Republican Governor in a democratic, par excellence state.
He is in second place in the approval rating among the 50 governors of the country.
Hogan is not a stubborn reactionary.
He demonstrated a firm hand in the management of the state and commitment to his principles.
He also deftly uses Facebook as a primary way to connect with his constituents and with jokes showing his bald head on his page after chemotherapy.
Therefore, it is unnecessary and ultimately harmful to block people who come to the page of the Governor - which is declared as an official public forum and is conducted by the administration staff on taxpayers ' money.
In an interview with the Washington post, spokeswoman Amelia Ches defended the Governor's actions, arguing that blocking comments is just their moderation.
But it's too easy to use the image of trolls, spammers and haters spiteful on the Internet.
"Post" talked to some of the real people who were blocked by Hogan.
And these are real people, not trolls - a teacher, a businessman, a pastor who address their elected leaders.
They all say their comments were respectful, informative and not rude.
The pastor quoted the Bible, appealing to the fact that Hogan is a Catholic.
Lawyer Lakshmi Sarma Raman of Bowie, Maryland, did not Express hatred, but asked about hate crimes.
"I wrote a polite comment that I'm disappointed that he didn't respond to hate crimes and other recent news, "she wrote in the comments section of the article in the Post.
"I also don't like the idea that when a lot of people leave comments on the same topic, some immediately say it's a so-called cheat, instead of admitting that they're dealing with a large group of disgruntled citizens."
What the Governor's subordinates call a "concentrated spam attack," others would probably call an "active life position."
In the Facebook era, it's easy to tweak your image by simply blocking critics or erasing negative comments.
It's much less dusty, than before, when it was necessary to send the men to collect and burn the newspaper's critical editorials or arrest and gag the protesters.
But this is exactly what is happening now, only in numbers.
Hogen is not the first official to be criticized for not wanting to listen to Facebook and other social media.
President Trump was sued by Twitter users who were banned from his Twitter account.
One of the first landmark decisions on this topic was made this week in Virginia.
In the opinion of the district judge of the United States from Alexandria James K. Cacheris, Chairman of the Supervisory Council of the County of Loudon violated the First Amendment banned voter in your account in Facebook.
And in Kentucky, Republican Governor Matt Bain was presented with claims by the American Union for the protection of civil liberties for his behavior in Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
In Washington's time, the era of affordable postal expenses made about the same revolution as the Internet today.
From 1776 to 1800, the number of Newspapers quadrupled, and the authors of anonymous letters brought down his authority.
And even then, Washington was dealing with anonymous trolls.
People under the alias "Oricola", "Valerius", "Belisarius and Porcius" wrote letters in Newspapers deriding the decision of Washington.
According to historical documents collected by the online project "Documents of George Washington", his office was littered with petitions criticizing his position on the Treaty of friendship, trade and navigation.
But he didn't try to silence them.
Freedom of speech, dissent and speech is at the very Foundation of our state.
And true leadership means agreeing with it.
