Poverty and death in the Indonesian Golden land»
Cooking dinner, Bardin Degei not use the stove.
She doesn't even use the pot much.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of Paniai County in the rebellious Indonesian province of Papua, a housewife usually just puts sweet potatoes, which is called "note", directly into the hearth.
After half an hour, the charred tuber is taken out and eaten with impatient, unwashed hands.
Degei sits on an earthen floor-she has no furniture – and this is where she does her housework, such as washing clothes with muddy water from a nearby swamp.
The restroom is a bucket in a room without a roof.
She is the youngest of her husband's four wives, and so she was not assigned to work in the field.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: many men from this village are unemployed, many drink, and there are soldiers.
"Nobody dares to walk around the village after five in the evening," she says.
This is a rare opportunity to look at daily life in the Papua highlands, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 after a questionable referendum when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote, raising their hands in public in front of the occupying forces.
