The head of the EPA Pruitt refuses the intention to postpone the implementation of Obama's rules to reduce emissions
The next day, after a lawsuit by 15 States, the head of the Agency for environmental protection reversed its decision to defer implementation under the Obama administration rules designed to reduce emissions that pollute the air and lead to smog formation.
Pruitt explained his decision by the fact that now his Agency is more than in previous administrations, listening to the needs of regulators of environmental protection of individual States.
He did not mention a claim against his previous position filed with the Federal court of appeal.
The dispute revolved around the deadline of 1 October, by which the States should meet the 2015 ground-level ozone standards.
In June, Pruitt announced that he would postpone compliance for one year to give his office more time to study the plan and avoid "inconsistencies with local decisions or obstacles to economic growth."
Pruitt, who before being appointed by President trump to his current position as Oklahoma state attorney General, has long been known as a consistent opponent of tougher environmental regulations.
After moving to Washington, Pruitt has repeatedly blocked or postponed the introduction of rules that opposed the chemical or gas-oil industry.
The unexpected change of course on Wednesday is another legal defeat of the course taken by Pewitt to return to the former norms.
Last month, a Federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the EPA head exceeded his authority in an attempt to delay the Obama administration's rule requiring oil and gas companies to track and reduce methane leaks.
In a statement released Wednesday night, Pruitt suggested that, by drastically changing course on ozone standards, he was simply fulfilling the EPA's duty to cooperate with the States in the comprehensive process of timely implementation of the new standards.
"Under previous administrations, the EPA was often unable to meet the deadline, then waited for lawsuits from activist groups and others and discussed the timeline during the settlement of the case," Pruitt said, who filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA in his previous position.
"We do not believe in regulation through judicial processes, and we take the deadlines seriously.
We also take our Charter and the power it gives us seriously."
However, the EPA statement said that Pruitt may at some point re-use his" powers to delay and other powers given by law "to make sure that the"jcyjdfys" rules are on a clear course and on all available information."
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a broader revision of the ozone rules.
The bill, approved by the House of representatives last month, seeks to delay the implementation of the 2015 rules for at least eight years.
The Senate has not yet voted on this issue.
New York attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who led a coalition of States that filed a lawsuit against the EPA this week, said the group intends to continue legal pressure.
"The EPA's changes of course - after our lawsuits - are an important victory in the fight for the health and safety of 6.7 million new Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans, who are directly affected by smog covering their cities," Schneiderman said.
New York's suit was joined by California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, new Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode island, Vermont, and Washington, as well as the district of Columbia.
Ozone at ground level occurs when ordinary pollutants from machinery, power plants, refineries, chemical plants and other sources react with sunlight in the atmosphere.
