New results of tests to assess the age of asylum seekers in Sweden have been published
The latest results of the tests of asylum seekers in Sweden, who were subjected to a new method of medical age assessment, show that more than 80 percent of the tested were evaluated as persons over 18 years, but not all trust the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish national Agency for forensic medicine (Rättsmedicinalverket) started testing earlier this year.
They were designed to make the age assessment in the asylum process more accurate after the Swedish migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticized for not being able to determine the real age of some refugees claiming to be minors.
At the moment, Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing, and the forensic medicine Agency has now published the results of 2,481 tests for the period between mid-March and 31 July 2017.
Eighty per cent (2002) of the test subjects were rated as 18 years of age or older, and in another 25 cases, the forensic medicine Agency assessed that the test subject was "likely to be 18 years of age or older".
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person was "probably less than 18".
The tests are conducted only in cases where the age of the person is in doubt.
According to Johan Goransson from the Agency of forensic medicine, the results are consistent with the previous months.
"We do not see much difference with the statistics for the past months, the numbers are quite appropriate, "he told the portal"The Local".
The high proportion of cases in which people were assessed as having reached the age of 18 did not necessarily indicate that asylum-seekers had lied about their age.
In may, the Agency published the results of 581 tests and reported that in 442 cases,"the test taker is likely 18 years or older."
However, having considered 581 published results, the newspaper "Svenska Dagbladet" found that in 243 cases, a person openly stated that 18 he is executed this year.
The method of performing a medical age assessment, which consists in making an x-ray of wisdom teeth and tomography of knee joints and giving them to dentists and radiologists for analysis, has also caused criticism in some instances.
One of the sceptics is endocrinologist Claude Marcus from the Karolinska Institute, part of whose work is to assess the biological maturity of people in order to determine whether they have passed through puberty before or later than usual.
"I had reasons to think about it, and I don't think that it is necessary to use the methods of measurement that are used now.
Biological age is thus determined very inaccurately.
If we are unable to determine with certainty, we should not pretend you can," he told the newspaper "Metro".
However, Geranssen from the Agency of forensic medicine spoke in favor of the accuracy of the tests: "in General, we can say that the risk of mistaking a child for an adult is small.
The biggest risk we face when a person is about to be 18, in this case it is about 10 percent."
