The Bank of England will keep interest rates at 0.25%
It is expected that the Bank of England will later announce that interest rates will not change after weak economic growth and weakening inflation forced to subside rumors about a possible increase.
The Bank of England warned that economic growth will remain slow, and left interest rates unchanged amid growing pressure on family incomes.
Experts of the Bank's monetary policy Committee (MPC) voted with a result of 6 against 2 for the preservation of rates at the level of 0.25%, while this month fewer members of the Committee voted for an increase in the rate, because weak economic growth weakened support for the increase.
In its quarterly inflation report, the Bank limited its forecasts to an increase of 1.7% percent in 2017 and 1.6% in 2018 and warned that pressure on family incomes will continue, while it is still expected that inflation will rise to about 3% in the fall.
However, the Bank warned that rate hikes in the next few years would be necessary to control brexit-induced inflation, and said borrowing costs would probably have to be raised more than expected in the financial markets.
Also, the Committee members voted to abandon part of the huge set of measures for the development of the economy, launched a year ago due to brexit.
Starting next February, the Bank will close the emergency financing plan, which it provides cheap loans to banks, although he said that now he will have to provide another 15 billion pounds-up to 115 billion pounds.
In the Pro-rate decision Protocol, the Bank said:"according to the MPC's key forecasts, gross domestic product (GDP) growth will soon remain slow, while pressure on real household incomes continues to affect consumption."
On the issue of rates, he reiterated that "some tightening of fiscal policy" at a "slightly larger" size than markets expect " would be needed to halt inflation.
At the moment, the markets predict the first increase in the third quarter of next year and another one – in 2020.
But the Bank stressed that all increases will be" gradual "and"limited".
The Bank's forecasts for an increase this year and next year are lower than the forecasts made in may, which were equal to 1.9% and 1.7%.
The Bank left unchanged its forecast for 1.8% in 2018.
After the news, sterling fell against the dollar and the Euro.
The pound fell 0.5% to 1.31 us dollars and 0.4% to 1.11 euros.
The decision not to change the rate was made after the recent disappointing growth indicators weakened the increased expectation of an increase; GDP then rose 0.3% in the second quarter against 0.2% in the previous three months.
According to the representative of the Bank, the growth is likely to remain at 0.3% in the third quarter, although it will begin to increase slightly at the end of the year.
The Bank's latest inflation report gave little cause for joy to households hit by high inflation and very small wage increases: the pressure will increase before it falls.
The Bank added that the financial policy "cannot prevent" the Udo from earning in the next few years, but expects wages to "significantly" recover by the end of its three-year forecast.
The economy is also set to grow as a result of the growing demand for British goods, which is due to the low rate of the pound, which compensates for part of the reduced consumer spending.
The decision was made a year after last August, the rates were reduced to 0.25% after the shocking results of the referendum on the exit from the European Union, which led to the fall of the pound.
The Bank estimates that it will likely take four years to fully impact prices and the economy.
Before the Bank made its last decision on rates, there was growing noise around the proposed rate hike, as inflation was increasingly pressing on already heavily pressured households: three Committee members asked for a rate hike of 0.5% in July.
Last month, inflation fell to 2.6 percent from 2.9 percent in July, although the Bank said the fall was expected and will be compensated again in the coming months.
