The state health service will prescribe a controversial drug for HIV 10,000 people
Starting in September, patients will have access to a" revolutionary " drug for HIV prevention after the battle in the High court on the financing of the drug from The public health service.
National health service England announced that pre-exposure prophylaxis of HIV (Prep), a pill taken before sex, which has been shown to reduce the risk of infection in individuals who are at risk, on average, 86 percent, will now be provided by the health service during the initial three-year probationary period of about 10,000 people.
She agreed to Fund the trial after the court of appeal upheld a High court ruling last year alleging that the National health service had the ability to pay for Prep despite her claims that it should be funded by local authorities.
The move, announced on Thursday, was called a "major innovation" by President Simon Stevens of the national health service of England, and the national AIDS control authority (NAT) called it a "turning point."
Before the full launch of the program across England by April 2018, venereal clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to register people, and even more dispensaries will join the program in October.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (Prep) is a course of HIV drugs taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that Prep significantly reduces the risk of HIV infection among people at risk.
When taking Prep before sex in the human body, a sufficient number of certain drugs to prevent infection with HIV.
Such drugs can be taken daily or no later than two hours before sex.
Patients eligible for the drug include homosexual and bisexual men, transgender people and people whose partners are HIV-positive and do not receive successful treatment.
The dispensaries will select suitable participants who have agreed to participate in the study, including men, women, transgender people and those whose partners are unknown, whether their HIV status is being held back by antiretroviral therapy.
People living and assigned to a General practitioner in England will also be able to apply for potential participation in the nearest venereal clinic taking part in the program.
The program will cost 10 million pounds, and the national health service of England this week after the international tender for the purchase signed an agreement on the provision of the drug.
The study is designed to evaluate all the possibilities of Prep by collecting clinical data on who is the target audience of the drug, its digestibility and use on a large scale.
"This crucial innovation should complement and strengthen the large-scale and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
This is another milestone in more than three decades of success in the fight against one of the biggest health threats facing humanity.
Deborah gold, President of NAT (National AIDS control authority), said: "this is a turning point in the fight against HIV.
Prep, if competently targeted at people in need and at risk, provides an opportunity to change the situation with the HIV epidemic in England.
Starting in September, people at risk for HIV, thanks to this study, conducted in England at the expense of the National health service, will have access to a new opening up means, the use of which the person can control himself, without discussing it with a partner, which will lead to the improvement of many, many lives.
We warmly welcome this news."
Ian green, President of the Terrence Higgins Foundation, said: "the first thing we need to do Now is to make sure that the test is fast-paced across the country and that no one at risk for HIV is forgotten.
Now that we have been provided with an experimental prep drug, we are moving to protect more than 10,000 people at risk for HIV."
Shadow Minister of public health Sharon Hodgson said:"We very much welcome the start of the Prep test, it is very late because of months of delays and procrastination on the part of the government."
