Judges were asked to defend from the chairmen
The presidential Council for human rights (HRC), on behalf of Vladimir Putin, has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The HRC proposes to limit the powers of court presidents and introduce their election.
For courts of appeal and cassation instances, the HRC wants to introduce special districts that will not be tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme court should also submit its proposals within the framework of the presidential instruction.
The HRC has completed the development of proposals that will strengthen the independence of the Russian justice.
This work was carried out by the HRC on behalf of Vladimir Putin on January 3, 2017, which the President gave after a meeting with members of the Council.
At a meeting with the Council members on December 8, 2016, they discussed, among other things, some cases of judicial arbitrariness, as well as problems of public control in places of detention of citizens (see "Kommersant" on December 9).
The outcome of the HRC work was 25 proposals, which relate to both issues of ensuring the independence of judges and identifying judicial errors, and the financing of courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of the Kremlin human rights activists is to limit the powers of the court presidents to increase the independence of the other judges.
If the candidate for the position of judge successfully passed the competition and received the support of the judicial community, the Chairman of the court, according to the HRC, should submit him to the appointment, not having the right to refuse, as it allows now the law.
It is also proposed to deprive the President of the right to distribute cases between the judges.
Experts admit that a specially written computer program can do this.
Also in the HRC, we believe that the Chairman shall not have the right "to predetermine the outcome of the qualification attestation of a judge, to initiate the institution of disciplinary proceedings, to make decisions on the establishment of additional material benefits".
At the same time, the presidential Council considers it necessary to move to "the election of court presidents by the judges themselves" and "to give them powers for a relatively short period with mandatory rotation".
Now all court presidents (from Republican to district) are appointed for six years by the President on the recommendation of the Chairman of the Supreme court.
In order to protect judges from the pressure of regional administrations, the HRC proposes to organize an appeal and cassation in courts of General jurisdiction in a new way.
Now their structure is tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The HRC says that"it is necessary to ensure the organization of individual courts of appeal and cassation instances not at the level of regional judicial bodies in the subjects of the Russian Federation, but in judicial districts."
Experts take as a basis the practice of arbitration courts.
They have " judicial districts "that do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but guarantee greater independence from regional officials, who find it difficult to use"telephone law".
The HRC proposes to strengthen the justices of the peace with the participation of people's assessors to consider some "categories of civil and administrative cases".
For example, the deprivation of parental rights, the restoration of the work, the protection of honor and dignity, the deprivation of driver's rights, etc.
"These are only our proposals, "explained" Kommersant " member of the HRC, the judge of the constitutional court in resignation Tamara wrinkle.
She also recalled that the President's instruction related not only to the HRC, but also to the Supreme court (SC), which has not yet disclosed its proposals.
Time for the execution of orders from the sun (among the co - prosecutors-the Prosecutor General and the Commissioner for human rights in Russia) is still there.
Chairman of the Supreme court Vyacheslav Lebedev should report to Vladimir Putin on how effectively the independence of justice is ensured in Russia by September 1.
