"In Libya, we do not want to be associated with any of the parties to the conflict"
The government recently stepped up its policy in the Libyan context, and visits to Moscow were frequent delegations of the warring Libyan parties.
The Russian head of the contact group for the inter-Libyan settlement with the Ministry of foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation and the state Duma, the assistant to the head of the Chechen Republic Lev Money told "Kommersant", what is the objective of Moscow in the region and who is betting.
The contact group on Libya, which you head, is almost unknown.
Here, say, the contact group for Ukraine-everyone knows about it.
And here is the veil of mystery.
What exactly do you do, what are your goals?
The contact group was established on the initiative of the Russian foreign Ministry and the state Duma.
Its activities are supervised by Deputy foreign Minister Mikhail Bogdanov and Adam Delimkhanov (Duma Deputy from Chechnya. - "B").
The latter is authorized to work in the Libyan direction by the speaker of the state Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
The impetus for the creation of the group was the detention in Libya of the Russian tanker "Mechanic Chebotarev" (in September 2015, there were 11 people on Board. - "B").
We thought about how to help the crew.
Then a contact group of military experts, representatives of the state Duma was created, our work was supported by the head of Chechnya Ramzan Kadyrov.
And how did it happen that you headed it?
Since I have been working in Libya since 2008, I have been approached with a proposal to lead the group.
Our activities were not limited to the release of sailors from the "Mechanic Chebotarev".
We managed to establish contacts with representatives of all major groups opposing each other in the Libyan conflict - and from Tripoli (where the UN-recognized government headed by Faiz Saraj is based. - "Kommersant"), and with Tobruk (the residence of the Parliament, which opposes the government and supports Marshal Khalifa Haftar, who controls the Eastern regions of Libya. - "B").
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metig (Deputy Prime Minister of Libya-Kommersant), we were able to quickly agree on the release of Russian sailors.
Then it was decided to use these contacts more effectively, to create a contact group.
Its task is to analyze the situation, identify key factors and players, and dialogue with all parties to the conflict.
I want to emphasize that in Libya we do not want to be associated with any of the parties to the conflict, we are engaged in a dialogue with all.
How many people are in the contact group and how many of them are permanently in Libya?
Now the contact group consists of five people.
Among them there are people with experience in law enforcement agencies, including the Ministry of defense.
We also want to introduce representatives of the middle East Institute of the Russian Academy of Sciences to the regional team.
None of our employees are constantly in Libya, and this is not necessary.
Is there now in Libya, Russian military advisers and instructors.
And if so, on whose side?
There are no Russian military specialists in Libya.
All conversations and publications about this are not true.
But your contact group includes ex-military...
Yes, and their presence is necessary.
For example, when we visit hot spots.
Or such cities closed to a certain point for us, as Misrata (where militia groups are based, which played a role in the overthrow of the Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in 2011 and significantly intensified in subsequent years. - "B").
We arrived in Misrata in January of this year.
We were scared, saying that they're all Islamists are terrorists.
But it was important for us to assess the situation there, to analyze the real military potential, who is responsible for what, why there are such rumors, what is the role of Islamists there.
In Misrata, we met with all the representatives of the groups that were engaged in the destruction of the is in Sirte (in December 2016, this city on the Mediterranean coast was repulsed from the militants of the banned in Russia "Islamic state" - "Kommersant").
We wanted to look at them, to get to know these people, to check the information that they played a crucial role in the destruction of the is in Libya, and not the Khalifa Haftar, who attributed himself to these merits.
And what did you conclude?
Is it not Haftar who won the Islamic state in Libya?
He didn't.
Haftar conducted operations on another front, in Benghazi.
And the structures subordinated to the government in Tripoli fought against ISIS in Sirte.
By the way, we invited people who conducted this anti-terrorist operation to Russia.
And they came-the visit lasted from 19 to 23 April this year, the Libyan delegation was received by the Federation Council, the Duma, the foreign Ministry and Regardie.
You, as we understand, visit all Libyan regions and probably imagine the mood of local elites and field commanders.
What do you think, will it be possible to implement the ceasefire agreements, the elections that were reached in late July in Paris by Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Saraj?
Or again, as it has repeatedly happened in the past, the agreements will be broken, the fighting will resume, the parties will try to seize power alone?
For us, a good signal was the fact that Saraj and Haftar agreed to the next meeting, not so long ago it was impossible.
In the recent past, both leaders have spoken very negatively about each other.
As for the position of Russia...
Often write and say that Moscow actively supports Haftar, many believe in it.
We faced this situation when we were in Misrata, and it was on this day that Haftar was on Board the Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov.
It was coincidence.
But in Misrata in the match is not believed.
We were told: "You must be very brave people that came to us today".
But our task is precisely to show that we do not only support Haftar, we are engaged in a dialogue with all the key parties to the conflict in Libya.
You and Haftar talked.
Does mutual understanding with Russian partners at a human, emotional level facilitate the fact that he studied in the USSR twice?
And, by the way, does Haftar know Russian?
Russian if he knows it is very concerning.
But the fact that he studied with us, of course, facilitates dialogue with him.
And by the way not only with him.
When we communicate with the military in Tripoli and Misrata, we meet generals who studied either in Russia or in the Soviet Union.
And here they are perfectly speak Russian.
And they are drawn to Russia, to some extent feel nostalgia for it.
Do you think the weapons embargo imposed on Libya will be lifted soon?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in the supply of Russian weapons?
Of course, they are interested, but, as I said, we do not take sides in this conflict and do not want to arm some to the detriment of others.
We would like to see everyone in roughly equal positions.
With regard to the arms embargo, from the Libyans constant calls to Russia somehow has contributed to its removal.
Now Libya is actively moving the process of drafting a Constitution.
We hope that the parties will reach compromise solutions and achieve internal consensus.
Then, elections should be held, what was discussed at the meeting Saraga and the Haftarot.
If the elections are held and the legitimate government is finally elected (and now none of the parties has such status), then it is possible to raise the question of lifting the arms embargo in the UN security Council.
To raise this issue now is meaningless and dangerous, it will only lead to an escalation of the conflict.
Recently, the media reported that Italy, faced with the problem of floating from Libya African refugees, feels left to their fate by the EU allies.
Can Moscow help its Italian partners in this situation, using its ties with the Libyans?
How realistic, for example, is the option that Haftar troops will establish control over the coast and put an end to the business of smugglers who smuggle immigrants to Europe?
Very timely question.
We are actively working on this.
The Italians need Russia's support, because Moscow is engaged in a dialogue with Haftar, Saraj, Misrata and the South of the country.
And in this matter the tribes in the South of Libya play a big role, and they are ready to cooperate with Russia.
We are talking about the southerners to stop the flow of migrants on the distant approaches?
That is, relatively speaking, turned back the buses, which go Nigerian migrants?
We achieve this.
But it's not easy.
Some clans and groups are interested in these flows to continue.
We hope to contribute to the unification of the South in the negotiation process between Saraj, Haftar and the tribes in the South.
But first, we would like to see a unity of opinion on this issue between Haftar and Saraj.
The head of government in Tripoli, Faiz Saraj, is considered an Islamist, a supporter of the introduction of Sharia in the country.
How radical do you think he is?
Will this not be an obstacle in building relations with Russia or the West?
I will Express my personal opinion about him.
In my opinion, on the contrary, he is an opponent of radical Islam.
But the Islamists are in his coalition.
Yes, but he himself holds the position that Libya should be an absolutely normal country - moderately Islamic, open to the world.
And he is also actively fighting terrorists.
Where did he get such a reputation?
It was created by those countries that are not interested in Russia communicating with Tripoli.
Tripoli is the capital, there is the legislative, Executive and judicial power.
There is the national oil Corporation, the national Bank and other government agencies.
Of course, some countries were interested in us not to go there.
And we mixed them all the cards and began to actively communicate with both Tripoli and Tobruk.
And we are already reaping the fruits of this work: Rosneft has signed a cooperation agreement with the state oil company of Libya - NOC.
NOC Director Mustafa Sanalla, with whom the head of Rosneft Igor Sechin made a deal, himself directly from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago, the first shipment of Libyan oil to Rosneft took place.
What will Russia do with it?
I suppose it's reselling.
And what are Russia's economic interests in Libya?
The plans are to re-sign the contracts signed under Muammar Gaddafi.
In particular, we are talking about previous agreements in the transport sector (construction of Railways), energy (electrification) and a number of others.
And the Libyans have something to pay?
Well, they've got oil.
That is, as in the case of Iran, we are talking about the scheme "oil in exchange for services"?
I do not know what will be the scheme, I do not deal with these issues directly.
In fact, the economy for Russia in Libya and not the main thing.
In fact, we are engaged in peacekeeping work there.
The main thing for us is to stop the bloodshed and help the Libyans to agree among themselves so that they can establish order and Libya will no longer be a favorable environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, this is the main task - to help the Libyan people and squeeze out terrorists.
Do you have any information about the presence in Libya (now or before) of radical militants from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to find out.
I met with a representative of the Libyan state security Committee, who said that to date, no one comes from Russia and other countries of the former Soviet Union there.
He said that he has about 50 thousand records of telephone conversations of representatives of Islamist and radical groups (in Libya. - "Kommersant") and the Russian language, there is no sound.
And from what States then these fighters?
I would not like to go into these details.
Then let's formulate the question differently.
How many among the Islamist militants in Libya Libyans themselves?
Libyans among them almost no, they are not more than 5%.
The others are strangers.
Whether Moscow can hold the inter-Libyan talks, following the example of Paris?
Such plans exist.
We are in active negotiations with Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow, and have declared their readiness to come to Moscow or Grozny.
And when can such negotiations take place?
It's hard to tell right now.
There should be several more visits, and then, I hope, there will be clarity about the time and place of negotiations.
