Michelle Carter's sentence for reports of Conrad Roy's suicide
A resident of Massachusetts was sentenced to two and a half years in prison for using text messages and phone calls to incite the suicide of her boyfriend Conrad Roy.
Michelle Carter, now 20 years old, will have to serve 15 months of her time behind bars and another 5 years of probation.
Carter was found guilty in June of manslaughter of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy's father said at a hearing on Thursday, " My family is heartbroken.
My son was my best friend."
Carter was allowed to remain free until the appeal.
She was facing a maximum sentence of 20 years, but her lawyers said she and Roy were both mentally ill.
Carter, dressed in red trousers and a cream blouse, listened to the sentence standing with her hands and eyes down.
"Her actions killed Conrad Roy," the Prosecutor told the court.
"She interrupted his life to improve her.
She did not accept responsibility, " she said.
"She showed no remorse."
But Carter's lawyer said that it was "a tragic case that she deeply regrets."
However, judge Lawrence Monis said that, in his opinion, her "age, maturity level, or even mental illness did not significantly affect her actions."
The Prosecutor read out the statement of the mother of Roy, Lynn, Roy, which says: "there is not a day when I would not have mourned the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and how I'm doing - I try to support his sisters, despite all the pain that will remain with us forever," it says.
Roy's sister Camdin Roy said that she was relentlessly haunted by the idea that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become an aunt to his children.
"To lose the person who has been with me always since my birth is a pain that will remain with me until the end of life," she said.
This case is likely to become a legal precedent, as Massachusetts does not have a law that would provide for responsibility for advising a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in a car with symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The case attracted the attention of the whole country when it became known that he was pushed to suicide by Carter's message.
"You can hang yourself, jump off the roof, stab yourself with a knife I do not know there are many ways," she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death, when he was resting with his family.
A few minutes before the suicide, she wrote, "you have to do this, Conrad," and "you just have to turn on the ignition, and you'll be free and happy."
Judge Monis said that Carter wanted to get attention with Roy's death, and he told her not to talk to the press to keep her from getting what she wanted.
The opinions of lawyers on this matter are divided.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 for the murder in Italy of her British roommate and acquitted two years later.
30-year-old Knox published in the Los Angeles times his dissenting opinion, which stated: "Michelle Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison."
