Dinosaur used camouflage to avoid enemies
At first glance, he seems to be a statue, though terrifying.
The researchers said that the first remains of an incredible creature the size of a rhinoceros discovered by a canadian miner, preserved so well that experts called it "Mona Lisa among dinosaurs."
It was so well preserved that they were even able to determine that the color of its scaly skin was reddish-brown – and say that it had, in some way, a "dark past."
In a report published in the journal of modern biology, It was described as "the best-preserved of the thyroid Gland in the history of finds and one of the best dinosaur specimens in the world."
This fossil is a recently found specimen of the nodosaurus, which lived in the middle of the Cretaceous period, between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
His incredible good condition has stunned researchers who call him"truly remarkable."
This herbivorous therefor is the most well-preserved fossil of this type in the history of discoveries according to articles in the National Geographic magazine.
He was found by Sean Funk while he was working at the Sunkor Millennium mine near Fort McMurray in Northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
He came across something that seemed different from the surrounding breed and decided to look closer.
The fossil he discovered was sent to the Royal Tirrell Museum of paleontology.
For the next six years, work was carried out to detect an animal inside a block of earth weighing 2500 feet (1100 kilograms).
