"One has only to squint slightly, and you can almost believe that he is asleep," - said the lead author Caleb brown, a researcher at the Royal Tirrell Museum of paleontology, which demonstrates the creation.
"It will go down in the history of science as one of the most beautiful and best preserved dinosaur specimens – the Mona Lisa among the dinosaurs."
Studying its skin, the researchers found that it was a herbivore, despite the fact that it was covered with a shell and resembled a walking tank, apparently exposed to considerable danger from carnivorous dinosaurs.
This powerful armored dinosaur used a red and white camouflage to hide from predators, and used a protective technique known as protective coloring, which is also used by many animals of our days.
This would allow him to quickly merge with the surrounding environment and avoid meeting enemies, experts say, assuming that it was hunted by larger dinosaurs.
This 110 million-year-old creature, belonging to the nodosaur family, was widely published in may, and is now on display at the Royal Tirrell Museum of paleontology.
Scientists have already studied the animal and gave it the name Borealopelta markmitchelli in honor of the Museum laboratory assistant Mark Mitchell, one of the members of the group, who spent more than 7,000 hours for his painstaking excavations.
The amazing preservation of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of the scales and the shell plates on his body.
They found a protective color, a common method of protection in the animal Kingdom, which means that the top of the creature was darker than its underside.
Although protective coloration and well-distributed, the discovery came as a surprise because the size Of the borealopelta dinosaur is much larger than the size of living animals with protective coloration.
It can be assumed that this dinosaur was so actively hunted by carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution chose to disguise confrontation as a way of survival.
But most modern animals with protective coloration – for example, deer, zebras, or armadillos – much smaller and are more available prey, indicating that nodosaur had to seriously fight for survival.
"The serious threat from predators to a massive, heavily armored dinosaur shows how dangerous the predatory dinosaurs of the Cretaceous period were," brown said.
Chemical analysis of organic compounds in the dinosaur scales also suggests that his skin should have been reddish-brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal, looking for information about his life, including the preserved contents of his digestive tract, to find out what he ate during his last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into the river and was taken to the sea, where it sank and lay back down to the bottom of the ocean.
It was as warm as it is now in southern Florida in those days in Alberta, and the rivers and oceans were likely to extend much further inland than they are now.
"This nodosaurus is truly remarkable for being completely covered with preserved scaly skin, and at the same time fully preserved in three dimensions, while maintaining the original shape of the animal," brown said.
"As a result, now the animal looks almost the same as it did then, in the Early Cretaceous.
You don't have to use your imagination to recreate it, you only have to squint a little, and you can almost believe that he is asleep."
The Cretaceous period is an era when giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs standing on two legs, roamed the Earth.
