This is the result of two years of correspondence between Dewey Harborg, whose art combines technology, computer science and art, and manning, a transsexual woman and a famous dissident, whom Barack Obama commuted his sentence just three days before the end of his presidency.
After analyzing the DNA obtained from manning with the help of a computer program and using it to create three-dimensional portraits of faces that could be found in people with such a genome, Dewey - Harborg created a deep, though not easy to perceive Manifesto devoted not only to the plasticity of DNA data - the various ways of their interpretation and the in-patient determinism of these interpretations-but also to the concept of identity.
Manning, who was born with the name Bradley Edward, but since her Teens has openly said she considers herself a woman, was sentenced to 20 episodes in 2013, including six violations of the espionage Act, computer fraud, and theft.
Her photos in prison were not available, so only one photo of her was known: a grainy black and white selfie, on which manning in a platinum-toned wig, obviously feeling awkward, sitting behind the wheel of the car; with this photo it and began to associate.
In 2015, Dewey Harborg completed her 2012 project "Visions of strangers"with great success.
In it, the artist created portraits of unknown people with the help of forensic evidence such as cigarette butts and chewing gum, highlighting the DNA of this garbage and creating images of how these people could look.
And then she received an email from Paper Magazine.
"They interviewed Chelsea manning in prison and wanted some portrait to illustrate the article," Dewey-Hagborg explained at a pre - screening of the new exhibition for the press.
At the time, Chelsea was not allowed to visit and take pictures, so they contacted her and asked if she wanted a portrait created from her DNA.
In such an unusual way, the artist and her imprisoned Muse became pen pals and exchanged several letters over the course of two years.
They even wrote a comic book "Suppressed images," illustrated by Daily, Kanungo that depicted how the future President will commute a penalty to Chelsea and she will be able to visit the exhibition in person.
The fact that Obama actually decided to release manning just a few days after the book was published was a pleasant surprise after seven hard years in a military prison in Kansas.
There is something profound and powerful about the exhibition opening right now, when Donald trump is declaring war on people revealing classified information in the government and inventing new ways to incite hatred on Twitter, which he is designed to mitigate.
When Dewey Harborg was asked about the coincidence of this all on time, she said that "nothing happens by accident."
In the artist's statement, written on the wall of Galeria, manning's huge signature at the bottom (with a heart instead of a dot over the "i" in her last name) calls for an end to "automatic separation based on gender, race, sexual orientation and culture."
On the opposite side are her mitochondrial DNA, a long caterpillar written in pencil C, G, and A.
With 200 letters (or nucleotides, as the artist has scientifically described), Dewey Harborg hoped to show how remarkably similar we all are, at least in our biological structure.
"I hope to explain to people that our genome doesn't determine what we are, how open genetic data is to interpretation, and how subjective it is," said Dewey Harborg; her 2007 video work False memories is also on display here.
"DNA data can tell us a lot of different stories, and 30 of those stories are here."
The last part of the exhibition, which fit in one room, is the above - mentioned novel in comics.
It manning in the style of king Kong appears over the building of the us Correctional Barracks with a loudspeaker in his hand.
"If they kill your speech, they will win," it says there.
"So never shut up."
"It's a direct quote from a letter she wrote me," says the artist, greeting us from Philadelphia.
"I still get goosebumps when I talk about it."
Manning had not yet seen the exhibition in person - as was visionary in the comics-but when she arrived, she would be greeted by masks in the center of the room, her own genomic simulacra gathered like a crowd of protesters.
This is also done deliberately, as everything in the exhibition up to the height (5"2, height manning), which was drawn in pencil genetic haplogroups.
"I used to hang them on the walls, but now I want them to look like a crowd of people," says Dewey Harborg about the portraits.
