Now there is a new kind of start-UPS in the field of human resources, which help companies to find out how their employees feel.
Developing and licensing software, the purpose of which is to measure employee engagement, they enable companies to do quick polls, to access certain commands and demographic groups, to offer employees anonymity and a hot line for complaints, and in some cases allow whistleblowers to bypass top management and go directly to the Directorate.
"Now we have tools like Strava and Fitbit for health monitoring, and where is Fitbit for your company?"says Jim Barnett, co-founder and President of the Redwood city startup, whose analytical programs are used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Errett said that she has reached a greater understanding of what her employees think and feel for three years of using "Glint".
In addition to the Express surveys and questionnaires of certain teams, the product offers a heat map of the company and shows in a visual form which departments have more complaints and which managers have a low approval rating, which allows it to understand why.
Companies gradually realize that they need to control the situation in the workplace, otherwise they will become another "Uber", which was involved in a scandal when a former employee published a blog post in which he described the aggressive environment in which those who expressed dissatisfaction were punished.
For such startups as" Glint", this desire to control the situation is an opportunity for profitable business.
According to the Internet portal "Let's talk about payment", dedicated to financial technologies, the industry of global management, regulation and compliance by 2020 can cost more than 118.7 billion dollars.
Convercent startup from Denver, Colorado, helping companies prevent and detect bad behavior, noted a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year amid uber's declining reputation.
Convercent has almost 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently clients came to "Uber".
Like the" Glint"," Convercent " allows companies to send custom-made surveys of staff opinions, collect confidential responses in real time and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages that allows employees to report bad behavior.
And if the top Manager is affected, the complaints go directly to the Directorate.
"The court of public opinion seized power from the inspectors, "said Patrick Quinlan, founder and President of Convercent.
If it turns out that the company is mistreating employees or behaving unethically, even if the inspectors do not intervene, the company may face costly consequences in the form of boycotts by customers, employee outflows and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain with over 25,000 employees in 500 establishments, has used Convercent for over a year to ensure that employees are up to date with the rules and procedures, and to offer an easy way to contact the company's head office.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report a problem, he or she had to search for a head office phone number or email, file a formal complaint, and hope that she would be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and awkward experience, said James Vitrano, head of the legal Department at Ruby Tuesday, who said that there was no normal way to track employee complaints.
Now that the company is using Convercent, problems that were previously hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or States – such as discrimination, harassment, and unfair pay – can be found and addressed more quickly.
"I can get closer to a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the employees' situation, "said Vitrano, who leads the risk management group of the Ruby Tuesday network.
"And we protect our shareholders from litigation with employees."
According to Quinland, companies began to take ethics, values, and employee engagement more seriously in 2002, after Arthur Andersen's accounting firm collapsed due to ethical violations as a result of the Enron Case.
But it was only when "social media got widespread," that companies realized they couldn't keep their dirty Laundry from spreading viral on the web.
"Before using technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy," he said.
Both "Glint" and "Convercent" offer their software as a service, charging companies a regular fee for the use of their products.
This business model and opportunity, which received the approval of venture investors who have supported both start-up.
In February, "Convercent" received funding in the amount of $ 10 million from such firms as "Sapphire Ventures" and "Tola Capital", resulting in the total capital of the company reached $ 47 million.
Glint received $ 10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing the company's total capital to $ 60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising given the interconnected nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
A growing body of research shows that today's employees expect more of their jobs than they did before.
In highly competitive markets such as Silicon valley, high wages and interesting projects are just the bare minimum.
Employees want to feel accepted and valued, and that they dedicate their time to a company with a positive mission.
"When people are happy to work for a company, feel that they are being heard and that the work they are doing is producing results, they are more willing to make such a company a success, "says Nina McQueen, Vice President of global benefits and employee satisfaction at LinkedIn, where both Convercent and Glint are used.
Investors receive the income when the business of the companies from their portfolio are going well, companies are going well when people are committed and involved.
If third-party Analytics tools promise to increase employee loyalty and engagement, it's no wonder they find support.
According to cultural specialists in the workplace, it is important to have data on employee involvement.
But the data is useless until the company's Trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks employees for feedback, it may give the impression that change is coming.
And if change does not occur quickly enough, or not come at all, can develop frustration, and employees will lose interest.
"If you're going to ask for 4,000 offers, you should be prepared to have 4,000 conversations, "says Russell Rat, President of consulting at the management firm Kotter International, who has seen companies make a mistake by relying too much on data collection.
"Because if you don't go all the way, the staff will be wondering,' Did you really hear me?
You care?
And if you don't care, why should I care?»
According to Errett, Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly employee surveys, is able to take action the same day someone reports a problem with the help of "Glint."
And, after collecting feedback from employees unhappy with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining new knowledge about its employees and hopes that in the long term this knowledge will help it to retain employees in an industry known for high staff turnover more effectively.
"If you don't try to create a culture of transparency, you will lose people," Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
And if you lose customers, you lose companies.
