Red meat, dairy and chocolate can help ease the GCS.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent studies suggest the opposite: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help relieve symptoms in those suffering from inflammatory bowel diseases.
This incurable disease, which affects approximately 1.3 million people in the US and 300,000 in the UK, leads to colic and bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Usually, to alleviate the symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers from the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid protein tryptophan promotes the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells in the gut make sure that harmful microbes coming from food do not penetrate the body.
Cells that can trigger inflammation are balanced by cells that increase tolerance while protecting the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too much disturbed in the direction of inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice that have a certain bacteria in the intestine, there are cells that increase tolerance.
And this bacterium needs tryptophan, one of the building blocks of protein, to trigger these cells.
Professor Colonna said: "we have established a link between one type of bacteria, Lactobacillus reuteri, which is part of a normal gut microbiome, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more tryptophan they had in their mouse diet, the more immune cells they had."
He suggested that the same would work in humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet could promote a more tolerant and less inflammatory environment in the gut.
Postdoc Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Paraganas, studying the variation of increasing the tolerance of the immune cells, found that one group of experimental mice, these cells were, and the other group, which belonged to the same line, but separated, they were not.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by mouse gut microbiomes - communities of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of mouse gut cells was sequenced and six species of bacteria were found to be present in mice that have immune cells but are absent in mice that do not have them.
Mice grown in a sterile environment that did not have a good microbiome and did not develop this type of immune cells received L. reuteri, and immune cells appeared in them.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers raised L. reuteri in a liquid medium and then transferred small portions of the liquid - without bacteria - to underdeveloped immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells have turned into cells that increase tolerance.
When the active component was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan processing, known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in mouse food, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the level of tryptophan was halved, the number of cells also fell by half.
Dr. Cervantes-barragán explains that humans have the same tolerance-enhancing cells as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan by-products from L. reuteri contribute to the development of cells in humans as well as in mice, but defects in genes associated with tryptophan have been found in people suffering from inflammatory bowel diseases.
She says: "Perhaps the development of these cells and we need to strengthen, because these cells depends on the inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines.
High levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri can potentially lead to an expansion of their population."
