Props for the White house cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
According to the records of the armed forces, given the "TIME" magazine White house decision last month to drive the marine corps helicopter on the South lawn for the event, devoted to American industrial production, cost taxpayers as much as 24 000 dollars.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as" Marine One " when the President is on Board, became the Central element of the July 17 event held at the White house, which demonstrated the American construction program.
President Donald trump, Vice President Mike Pence and top White house officials have inspected technology products from all fifty States.
The helicopter, produced in Connecticut, was exhibited next to a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a forklift from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First squadron of the helicopters of the marine corps (HMX-1), the Department responsible for the control of the helicopter, the Military office of the White house ordered the presence of the helicopter in a private order, or "FRAGO", just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South lawn on the occasion of the "unusual" event.
"I just wanted you to make sure that you are aware, because this is an unusual widely reported event in the press," wrote the commander of HMX - 1 in an email to his boss, the first Deputy chief of the aviation corps of the marine corps, on the eve of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive on the South lawn at about 7 a.m. on 17 July to attend the 3 p.m. event and would remain there until the lawn was cleared between 6 and 9 p.m. the same day.
The letter adds that if the departure from the White house is delayed, a second crew will be required for the return flight in accordance with the working hours restrictions.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, and the security officers of the unit remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
From the records received by the magazine "TIME", it remains unclear whether it took in the end the second crew.
Hatch's law prohibits Federal employees from using state property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 clarified whether the event does not contradict this decision.
"Among other things, we asked if it was a violation of Hatch's law, and we were told that it was not," the commander wrote.
"It looks like you have nowhere to go," the Deputy chief replied.
The Made in America event was declared an official event by the White house, and Hatch's law did not apply to it.
But even formal events have a political tone.
During the event, the President made efforts to advance the health care reform that was then under development in the Senate, and touted attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as "Marine One" and "Air Force One" for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But it is unusual to request them only in the interests of photo opportunities.
Trump has already become the subject of debate in February, when a presidential plane rode in the background during his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account is littered with reports of complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessor.
"The white house is delighted with the show "Made in America", which presented products from 50 States made by American workers from American materials," said Deputy press Secretary of the White house Lindsay Walters.
The HMX-1 crews often perform training flights around the Washington agglomeration and on the South lawn to practice transporting the President of the United States to the White house down to an inch.
When trump was at the g-20 summit in Germany in early July, the HMX-1 held 58 training landings at the White house.
According to one of the officials, the flight performed for the event "Made in America" was counted to the crew on the account of the necessary training flights for the month.
The unit's helicopters also flew 11 additional hours that day as part of"non-resident support tasks".
According to the White house, the taxpayers did not bear the costs of any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
The representative of the company "Sikorsky" reported that the company was not involved in organizing a demonstration of the helicopter on the South lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep a budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But, according to the hourly rates of the Ministry of defense for fiscal year 2017, the rate of compensation of the Ministry of defence for the VH-3D is 24 380 USD per hour of flight.
The records of the unit recorded that the time of the aircraft in the air was 30 minutes each way from its airfield based at the aviation base of the marine corps of Quantico in Virginia.
The white house claims that the real cost of using the helicopter is much lower than this rate.
"Calculating the cost to taxpayers based on the estimated rate of reimbursement is completely wrong," says Walters.
"These sample rates include personnel, maintenance and many other irreversible costs that are included in the annual allocations."
According to a study conducted in 2015 by RAND Corporation, the reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but, indeed, take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance and costs specified in the contract.
At the time, former white house press Secretary Sean Spicer spoke out in defense of the use of the helicopter for the event.
"The idea is to showcase this week things made in America," Spicer said.
"And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to national security, and that there are, I guess, hundreds, if not thousands of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, we're all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly to build.
Therefore, of course, it is appropriate to pay attention to this."
It was unclear whether trump interacted with the helicopter while inspecting the South lawn during the event, but he definitely sat on the driver's seat in the fire truck.
Inside the White house, trump appealed to representatives of the company" Sikorsky", joking with the press about his own fleet of products.
"I know Sikorsky well," the President said.  I have three."
