Electricity is cheaper for residents and producers of Buryatia
The efforts of the Soviet and post-Soviet authorities of the Republic of Buryatia (Eastern Siberia) to establish fair tariffs for electricity consumers, which lasted for more than a decade, are beginning to bear fruit.
Since September 1, the cost of electricity in low voltage for industrial recipients has been reduced by 25%.
The Federal Antimonopoly service of the country in accordance with the RF Government Decree "On amendments to the Rules of the wholesale market of electric energy and capacity and a consolidated forecast balance of production and supply of electric energy (capacity) within the Unified energy system of Russia on subjects of the Russian Federation" (from down 17.07.2017, No. 842) set indicative prices for electricity and power for industrial consumers of the Republic of Buryatia.
As a result, the cost of electricity for Buryat producers is reduced by a quarter, which will greatly facilitate the life of small and medium-sized enterprises and individual entrepreneurs.
For many decades, the leaders of the Republic have been pounding the doors of Moscow offices in futile attempts to equalize the region in tariffs with the neighboring Irkutsk region with a cascade of hydroelectric power stations in the Hangar flowing from lake Baikal, the main catchment area for which is Buryatia.
And only this year the progress began.
In March, electricity tariffs for the population of the Republic are reduced from 4.24 rubles/kWh to 3.93 rubles/kWh, or 7.3%.
With the inclusion of Buryatia by the decision of the Federal government in the List of territories of price zones of the wholesale market, for which the features of the functioning of the wholesale and retail markets have been established, the turn of industrial consumers has come.
According to analysts, this is only the beginning, since the population of the Irkutsk region pays 1.01 rubles per kilowatt-hour.
But no one dares to name at least an approximate date of new tariff moves downwards for Buryatia.
